-------------------------------------------Numeric Types--------------------------------
1. Integer Types:
	INTEGER or INT: Standard integer type.
	BIGINT: Large integer (8 bytes).
	SMALLINT: Small integer (2 bytes).
	
2. Floating-Point Types:
	REAL: Single precision floating point (4 bytes).
	DOUBLE PRECISION or FLOAT: Double precision floating point (8 bytes).
	
3. Fixed-Point Types:
	NUMERIC(precision, scale): Arbitrary precision number (exact).
-------------------------------------Character Types-----------------------------
1.Character Types:
	CHAR(n): Fixed-length character string.
	VARCHAR(n): Variable-length character string.
	TEXT: Variable-length character string (unlimited length).
	
2.Date/Time Types
	Date/Time Types:
	DATE: Date (YYYY-MM-DD).
	TIME: Time of day without timezone.
	TIMESTAMP: Date and time including timezone.
	TIMESTAMP WITH TIME ZONE: Date and time with timezone.
	INTERVAL: Period of time.
	
-----------------------------------Boolean Type-----------------------------------
	BOOLEAN: Stores true/false values.
	
-----------------------------------Geometric Types----------------------------------
	Various types for geometric data such as points, lines, circles, polygons, etc.
	
------------------------------Network Address Types--------------------------------
	INET: IPv4 or IPv6 hosts and networks.
	CIDR: IPv4 or IPv6 networks.
	
------------------------------Arrays and Composite Types------------------------------
	ARRAY: Array of any data type.
	ROW: Composite type to represent a row of a table.
	JSON and JSONB Types
	JSON: Stores JSON data in text format.
	JSONB: Stores JSON data in a binary format (more efficient).
	
-------------------------Specialized Types-------------------------------
	UUID: Universally unique identifier.
	XML: Stores XML data.
	
--------------------------------Custom Types---------------------------
	PostgreSQL allows you to create your own custom data types using CREATE TYPE.
